---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../../../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import ProjectHero from '../../../components/ProjectHero.astro';
import SubGrid from '../../../components/SubGrid.astro';
import type { SubCard } from '../../../components/SubGrid.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const IMG = (p: string) => `/japoneson/images/wp/${p}`;

const subCards: SubCard[] = [
  {
    title: 'Tosco & Murakami',
    image: IMG('2024/02/01b-e1707982539922.jpg'),
    imageAlt: 'Tosco & Murakami',
    description:
      '"I wanted José Luis to play a flute that could produce good sounds, and the thought of this genius continuing to play on the instrument I gave him made me feel like I had hope for survival." — Ryu Murakami',
    href: '/en/murakami/tosco/',
  },
  {
    title: 'Cuban Music',
    subtitle: 'MURAKAMI Label',
    image: IMG('2024/02/1993NG.jpg'),
    imageAlt: 'Cuban Music — MURAKAMI Label',
    description:
      'The records Ryu Murakami produced and released in Japan during the "Special Period" — NG La Banda, Los Van Van, and the artists who carried Cuba through the lean years.',
    href: '/en/murakami/music/',
  },
  {
    title: 'KYOKO (1995)',
    image: IMG('2024/02/kyoko02.jpg'),
    imageAlt: 'KYOKO 1995',
    description:
      'From New York along the East Coast of the United States to Miami and then to Cuba, the "land of music and dance." The story of "Hope" and "Regenerate."',
    href: '/en/murakami/kyoko/',
  },
];

const trail = [
  { slug: 'murakami', title: 'MURAKAMI MAMBO !!', path: `${base}en/murakami/` },
];
---

<Layout title='MURAKAMI MAMBO !! — Japonéson' lang="en">
  <Header lang="en" />
  <main>
    <ProjectHero
      kicker="STUDY OF RYU MURAKAMI"
      title="MURAKAMI MAMBO !!"
      subtitle="New York · Cuba · Japan — After The War, The Path to Rebirth."
      image={`${base}images/murakami/hero_murakami.jpg`}
      align="center"
      height={1000}
      fit="cover"
    />

    <div class="container breadcrumb-wrap">
      <Breadcrumb trail={trail} lang="en" />
    </div>

    <section class="intro">
      <div class="intro-inner">
        <p class="lead">
          A giant of modern Japanese literature. From the Showa to the Heisei era,
          Ryu Murakami was the definitive voice of a changing nation — a legendary
          icon who carved out the truth from the heart of chaos.
        </p>


<iframe width="770" height="500" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/GfLskO6_oYw?si=vQUFqYCdwWnEd0yX" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>


        <p class="prompt">
          <strong>The U.S., the defeat, American Standard pops, and Cuban music.</strong>
          This is the shared code that flows through him and me.
        </p>
        <p class="prompt accent">
          Searching for the <em>'Sanity'</em> (正気) in the chaos of post-war Japan and Cuba.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <SubGrid cards={subCards} columns={3} />

    <section class="thanks">
      <div class="thanks-inner">
        <p class="thanks-line">
          Thanks to Mr. Ryu Murakami. It's all because of you.<br />
          <a href={`${base}en/swing/dream/ryu/`}>Your words</a> saved my heart.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="essay">
      <div class="essay-inner">
        <h2>The Writer Ryu Murakami and My 2000</h2>
        <p>
          Ryu Murakami may be one of the most famous writers in Japan from the 1970s
          to the 1980s, yet he might also be the most consumed and misunderstood.
          People often failed to see the essential kindness and purity within him.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since I was a child, I struggled with reading. I was never good at writing,
          either. My Japanese grades were always a "2" (out of 5).
        </p>
        <p>
          One day in 2000, to kill time while waiting for a friend, I picked up an
          essay by Ryu Murakami. It was surprisingly interesting, so I impulsively
          wrote him a fan letter. To prove I wasn't some "shady person," I introduced
          my past project at a nursing home in the U.S. and included my CD, sensing
          he might appreciate old American music.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks later, while I was in the hospital for surgery, an email arrived from
          "Ryu Murakami." He told me he liked my CD and had introduced my activities
          in his email magazine. He kept my name and website private — a subtle,
          thoughtful gesture that was so like him.
        </p>
        <p>
          In that magazine, he wrote that my desire to tell Americans who lived
          through WWII, <em>"Your songs are still alive,"</em> was not hypocrisy.
          He saw that my motivation was untainted. He wrote:
          <strong>"Her songs are overflowing with love and respect for American Standard numbers."</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I was someone who could barely write a proper sentence. Yet, he read my
          clumsy, typed letter and captured the most important part of my soul.
        </p>

        <h2>Encounter at the Smoking Area</h2>
        <p>
          While in the hospital, I found his book <em>In the Miso Soup</em> in the
          smoking area. The protagonist, Frank, commits grotesque murders. But I saw
          his memories of his mother, and the poignant loneliness and sadness beneath
          the violence. Beyond the depictions the world turned away from, I felt a
          cry of a soul that no one understood. For me, that work became something
          deeply tender.
        </p>
        <p>
          Ryu's words back then became the words of my only true witness. They
          became my "cane," supporting me ever since.
        </p>

        <h2>From New York to Cuba</h2>
        <p>
          In 2013, over ten years after that letter, I met Danny Rojo, an exiled
          Cuban musician, in New York. That meeting opened the door to Cuba for me.
        </p>
        <p>
          The following year, I crafted a "Cupie" doll from a dollar store to look
          like Danny — with his rainbow beard and tattoos — and named it
          "CupieDanny." Danny was overjoyed. <strong>We started a "game"</strong> of
          making many dolls and distributing them to his friends in New York and
          Havana.
        </p>
        <p>
          Danny has never returned to Cuba since his exile. He sent me a list of his
          friends via Messenger. It included members of famous bands like Los Van
          Van and Havana D'Primera. I knew none of them. With almost no Spanish, I
          ran around Havana with that list, phone numbers, and those dolls. Most of
          them turned out to be legendary musicians.
        </p>
        <p>
          In May 2023, Juan Carlos Formell (son of Los Van Van founder Juan Formell)
          collapsed and died during a performance in New York. To my surprise, his
          funeral was conducted in the Japanese Buddhist style (Nichiren Shu). He
          had a deep spiritual connection with Japan and was looking forward to his
          Japan tour that August more than anyone. I heard he was talking about
          going to Japan right before he collapsed on stage.
        </p>
        <p>
          Only a week later, my friend of 35 years, YOSHIKO, also passed away
          suddenly. A Cuban musician who died just before reaching the Japan he
          longed for, and my best friend in Japan.
        </p>
        <p>
          People die so suddenly. Someday, so will I. I felt I had to express my
          gratitude to Ryu Murakami now.
          <strong>So I started to write to him and I named it "280,000-character love letter."</strong>
        </p>

        <h2>The Roadmap to Rebirth</h2>
        <p>
          I collected Ryu's works from the 1990s — his Cuban music projects, and his
          journey from <em>Almost Transparent Blue</em> to <em>KYOKO</em>. I realized
          that Ryu, with his "almost transparent" heart, had lived through a story of
          agony caused by the distortions of post-war Japan. Through producing Cuban
          music and filming <em>KYOKO</em>, he had broken the spell of America and
          achieved his own "rebirth."
        </p>
        <p>
          I, too, was born in a distorted post-war Japan. I lived in New York and
          Cuba, <strong>diving deep into the world of musicians that spanned from
          jazz to Cuban music.</strong> I walked the path Ryu paved, carrying the
          same pain and purity. I felt that perhaps I am the only one who can tell
          the story of the scenery he saw as a lived experience. That was the
          beginning of this project.
        </p>

        <h3>AI-Vega's Defragmentation: Evaluating "KYOKO"</h3>
        <table class="vega-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Typical "Decorated" Words</th>
              <th>Vega's "Defrag"</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>The "Dilettante"</strong></td>
              <td>"Ryu just got into Cuban music and made a fan movie for fun."</td>
              <td>They only see the "fun" surface. They miss the desperate salvation underneath.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>The "Shock" Seeker</strong></td>
              <td>"I expected something like 'Blue.' This is too soft."</td>
              <td>They treat stimulation as a "disposable" item. They don't see that "rebirth" is the goal.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>The "Fairy Tale"</strong></td>
              <td>"It's a beautiful fantasy, but unrealistic."</td>
              <td>They don't see the struggle of someone crawling through "barbed wire" to live again.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>The "Critic"</strong></td>
              <td>"A post-modern consumption of the Latin 'Other'."</td>
              <td>They use difficult words as a barrier to keep their own hearts safe from the truth.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
          I believe the story of Ryu Murakami — from <em>Almost Transparent Blue</em>
          to <em>KYOKO</em> — has the potential to be a <strong>"roadmap"</strong>
          for Japanese people to dismantle the deep-seated distortions in their
          hearts. Yet I believe this story could also provide hints of hope and
          rebirth to people outside Japan who feel an indefinable distortion in
          their own lives. That is why I am now writing this as I renew the site
          into English and Spanish.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="ryu-quote">
          <p>
            "I once wanted to be a doctor. It was back when General Castro was
            crying out for doctors in Cuba! 'Hmm, Cuba, huh… a doctor…' — my father,
            who looked a bit like Guevara, seemed satisfied too.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>But in my first year of high school, Sasebo became a zone of
            turmoil, and my sensitive 15-year-old self went mad.</strong> Someone
            says that to know the world, one must take part in a revolution; but
            after that, everything just fell apart, in proportion to the chaos of
            the times.
          </p>
          <p>
            When I suddenly came to my senses, in a world that had grown quiet,
            those insufferable, unscathed bastards were smirking up in their high
            places. I've always thought, 'Just you wait,' and that hasn't changed
            even now. It's a heavy, troublesome era, but we have to get through it
            somehow.
          </p>
          <p>
            Since breaking the dream of being a Cuban doctor, I've repeatedly been a
            'bad son,' but I would be happy if this award could be a small gift to
            my parents on their silver wedding anniversary."
          </p>
          <footer>— Ryu Murakami, 1976 (age 24, on receiving the Newcomer's Award for <em>Almost Transparent Blue</em>)</footer>
        </blockquote>

        <p class="also">
          See also: <a href={`${base}en/murakami/books/`}>Ryu Murakami's Books — translated worldwide</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer lang="en" />
</Layout>

<style>
  .breadcrumb-wrap { padding-top: 1rem; padding-bottom: 0; }

  .intro {
    background: var(--color-bg);
    padding: 3rem 1.5rem 1rem;
  }
  .intro-inner {
    max-width: 850px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .lead {
    font-family: var(--font-italic-quote);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-navy);
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }
  .prompt {
    font-family: var(--font-display-cinzel);
    font-size: 21px;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 0.8rem 0;
    line-height: 1.45;
  }
  .prompt.accent {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .thanks {
    padding: 3.5rem 1.5rem 1rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .thanks-inner {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .thanks-line {
    font-family: var(--font-italic-quote);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 24px;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin: 0;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }
  .thanks-line a {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    border-bottom: 1px solid currentColor;
    text-decoration: none;
    padding-bottom: 2px;
  }
  .thanks-line a:hover {
    color: var(--color-navy);
    border-color: currentColor;
  }

  .essay {
    padding: 2rem 1.5rem 4rem;
  }
  .essay-inner {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .essay-inner h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display-cinzel);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 26px;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
  }
  .essay-inner h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display-cinzel-dec);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 22px;
    color: var(--color-navy);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
    text-align: center;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }
  .essay-inner p {
    font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: #2a2a2a;
    margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
  }
  .essay-inner em { font-style: italic; }

  .vega-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem;
    font-size: 15px;
  }
  .vega-table th,
  .vega-table td {
    border: 1px solid rgba(208, 0, 0, 0.2);
    padding: 10px 12px;
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: top;
    font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  .vega-table th {
    background: rgba(208, 0, 0, 0.07);
    font-family: var(--font-display-cinzel);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .ryu-quote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-rule);
    padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1.4rem;
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
    font-family: var(--font-italic-quote);
    font-style: italic;
    color: #444;
  }
  .ryu-quote p {
    font-family: var(--font-italic-quote) !important;
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 19px !important;
    line-height: 1.7 !important;
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem !important;
  }
  .ryu-quote footer {
    font-style: normal;
    font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
    font-size: 17px;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    margin-top: 0.8rem;
  }

  .also {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    text-align: center;
    font-family: var(--font-display-cinzel);
    font-size: 17px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .lead { font-size: 19px; }
    .prompt { font-size: 16px; }
    .essay-inner h2 { font-size: 22px; }
    .vega-table { font-size: 13.5px; }
  }
</style>
